{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"18d5f81d-a220-48af-9cc8-9b2be111f830","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the **`webapi`** template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n### Example with auth:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain mydomain.onmicrosoft.com\n```\n\nYou can also add **JWT Bearer** or **Identity** manually via NuGet:\n- `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer`\n- `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Identity.EntityFrameworkCore`\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for the full list of options. Want me to scaffold a project for you?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1cdcfa69-76bd-4d26-9dc4-5de6551c9259","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.","outputTokens":299,"requestId":"9C07:164F8C:1CA9329:201D151:6A07BF5A"},"id":"7851b75b-657e-401a-9e50-789e2d8140f1","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:50:42.485Z","parentId":"cc22d962-b21e-4e17-b19a-b45c51fc0ef3"}
